{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"01e6fa48-eb5b-44d9-a298-f91a0e167199","content":"Here's how to configure `.vscode/mcp.json` for your C# MCP server:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Place this file at `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates with your server via stdin/stdout\n- Make sure your server implements the MCP protocol over stdio (not HTTP)\n\nIf you've published the server as a tool, you can use the compiled DLL instead:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"src/MyMcpServer/bin/Debug/net8.0/MyMcpServer.dll\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nAfter saving, VS Code will prompt you to start the server. You can also run **\"MCP: List Servers\"** from the command palette to verify it's detected.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4e466d64-6065-4e6c-918f-3dbc729117f7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":374,"requestId":"C032:1BD126:1BF535B:1F997A3:6A07C313"},"id":"0335d507-72fb-4b29-8fc7-b27fd674b538","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:06:35.143Z","parentId":"d57b6d31-66ac-4283-89ab-0ef01824c888"}
